{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13185"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13185"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.08,0.03,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42428"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of central chest discomfort, mild nausea, and shortness of breath. He describes the discomfort as a constant dull ache that started while he was working at his desk. He does not recall any precipitating triggers and has not noticed any positional changes. He has been well prior to the onset of his symptoms and has not experienced anything like this before.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history but mentions that his father had a \u0027heart problem\u0027 in his 40s that required hospitalisation. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally. His diet consists mainly of takeaway meals due to his busy work schedule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly anxious. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 128/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. Subtle thickening is noted over both Achilles tendons. Careful examination of his eyes reveals a faint greyish arc at the periphery of both corneas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis recent lipid profile shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol: 7.8 mmol/L (3.9-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDL cholesterol: 5.9 mmol/L (2.0-3.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL cholesterol: 1.1 mmol/L (1.0-1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriglycerides: 1.8 mmol/L (0.5-1.7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Based on the clinical findings and investigation results, which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myocardial infarction","Gastroesophageal reflux disease","Anxiety disorder","Costochondritis","Pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDespite the atypical and somewhat subtle presentation, this patient is likely experiencing a \u003Cstrong\u003Emyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E. Several factors support this diagnosis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. The patient shows signs suggestive of familial hypercholesterolemia (FH), a condition that significantly increases the risk of premature coronary artery disease. These signs include elevated LDL cholesterol, corneal arcus (the greyish arc around the cornea) at a young age, and Achilles tendon xanthomas (the subtle thickening noted). The family history of early heart disease also supports this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. While the chest discomfort is described as a dull ache rather than severe pain, atypical presentations of MI can occur, especially in younger patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. The associated shortness of breath and nausea are common symptoms accompanying MI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chest discomfort and is a common differential diagnosis for chest pain. However, GERD typically worsens when lying down and is often related to meals. It wouldn\u0027t explain the shortness of breath or the patient\u0027s risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E can present with chest discomfort, shortness of breath, and palpitations. However, the physical findings (corneal arcus, tendon xanthomas) and lipid profile abnormalities make this less likely as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECostochondritis\u003C/strong\u003E, an inflammation of the cartilage connecting the ribs to the breastbone, can cause chest pain. However, the pain is typically sharp and worsens with movement or pressure on the chest wall. It wouldn\u0027t explain the shortness of breath or the patient\u0027s risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E, inflammation of the pericardium, can cause chest pain that may be dull or sharp. However, the pain often worsens when lying down and improves when sitting up or leaning forward. A friction rub might be heard on auscultation, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s risk factors (likely FH) and symptoms, even though subtle, myocardial infarction remains the most concerning and likely diagnosis. This case highlights the importance of considering MI even in young patients, especially when risk factors are present, and the need for a high index of suspicion with atypical presentations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore details can be found on understanding how to diagnose FH in the references below.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Young individuals can suffer from a myocardial infarction, especially if they have predisposing conditions such as Familial Hypercholesterolemia.","Subtle signs of familial hypercholesterolemia include corneal arcus in young individuals and tendon xanthomas.","Atypical presentations of myocardial infarction can occur, especially in younger patients."],"references":["Vaezi Z, Amini A. Familial Hypercholesterolemia. [Updated 2022 Sep 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556009/","Athero. How to diagnose Familial hypercholesterolaemia. Australasia Network. n.d. Available from:  https://www.athero.org.au/fh/patients/diagnosis/#sas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42428"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13185"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42428"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-23T11:25:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-23T15:02:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5621"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56979"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1114"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chest pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-23T10:29:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T21:58:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic